      ExxonIt=E2=80=99s only a slight overstatement to say that, every year=
, every publicly traded oil company asks its shareholders to vote on a prop=
osal like this:RESOLVED: Shareholders request that ExxonMobil=E2=80=99s Boa=
rd of Directors issue an audited report to shareholders on whether and how =
a significant reduction in fossil fuel demand, envisioned in the IEA Net Ze=
ro 2050 scenario, would affect its financial position and underlying assump=
tions. The Board should summarize its findings to shareholders by January 3=
1, 2022, and the report should be completed at reasonable cost and omitting=
 proprietary information.Oil companies are at the center of debates over cl=
imate change. Many investors care a lot about climate change. Shareholders =
of public companies are, in some loose sense, the owners of those companies=
; they elect the directors of the companies and have some authority to tell=
 those directors what to do.=C2=A0In particular, a shareholder of a U.S. pu=
blic company can submit=C2=A0proposals for other shareholders to vote on in=
 the company=E2=80=99s annual proxy statement. Companies have to include th=
e proposals in their proxy statements =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, put them to a=
 vote of shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0unless they can find some reason to om=
it them. The rule (Rule 14a-8)=C2=A0gives companies lots of reasons to omit=
 proposals, and there is a certain amount of technical lawyering involved i=
n getting a proposal into a proxy statement. In particular, companies can o=
mit a proposal that =E2=80=9Cdeals with a matter relating to the company=E2=
=80=99s ordinary business operations,=E2=80=9D which means that shareholder=
s can=E2=80=99t really submit proposals like =E2=80=9Cyou should stop drill=
ing for oil so much.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CYou should write a report about oil =
drilling=E2=80=9D is usually fine.The proposal I quoted above is Item 6 of =
Exxon Mobil Corp.=E2=80=99s proxy statement this year. It was proposed by C=
hristian Brothers Investment Services Inc., which owns Exxon =E2=80=9Cshare=
s with a market value greater than $2,000.=E2=80=9D Here=E2=80=99s one from=
 Exxon=E2=80=99s proxy statement last year:Resolved: Shareholders request t=
hat ExxonMobil, with board oversight, publish a report, omitting proprietar=
y information and prepared at reasonable cost, assessing the public health =
risks of expanding petrochemical operations and investments in areas increa=
singly prone to climate change-induced storms, flooding, and sea level rise=
.That was proposed by =E2=80=9Cthe Park Foundation, a client of As You Sow,=
 ... the beneficial owner of 117 shares.=E2=80=9D If shareholders had voted=
 for this proposal,=C2=A0the effect would have been that, uh, Exxon=E2=80=
=99s shareholders would have requested that report. It is what is called a =
nonbinding (or =E2=80=9Cprecatory=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0shareholder proposal, and =
Exxon=E2=80=99s board and managers could have said =E2=80=9Cwe appreciate t=
he request but we have decided not to prepare that report.=E2=80=9DOr Exxon=
=C2=A0could have prepared a report and then kept doing what it was doing. T=
he nonbinding request was not =E2=80=9Cstop expanding petrochemical operati=
ons in areas prone to climate change-induced storms=E2=80=9D or whatever; i=
t was =E2=80=9Cwrite a report.=E2=80=9D The report could have said =E2=80=
=9Cmeh oil drilling is fine, we=E2=80=99re gonna keep doing it,=E2=80=9D or=
 it could have said =E2=80=9Cactually there are some significant risks, but=
 we=E2=80=99re gonna keep doing it.=E2=80=9D The shareholder proposal did n=
ot ask Exxon to change its business, just to write a report about it.Ultima=
tely only about 24.5% of Exxon=E2=80=99s shareholders voted for last year=
=E2=80=99s proposal, so it failed anyway.Like I said, this is an every-year=
 sort of thing.=C2=A0In 2016 there were a bunch of climate-related proposal=
s, including =E2=80=9Cclimate expert on board,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cpolicy to =
limit global warming to 2=C2=B0C,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Creport on impacts of cl=
imate change policies=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Creport reserve replacements in =
BTUs=E2=80=9D; they all failed.=C2=A0In 2017, a shareholder proposal=C2=A0a=
sked for=C2=A0=E2=80=9Can annual assessment of the long-term portfolio impa=
cts of technological advances and global climate change policies.=E2=80=9D =
Exxon opposed the proposal, noting that it already published annual climate=
-y reports with names like =E2=80=9COutlook for Energy=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9CEnergy and Carbon,=E2=80=9D but the proposal passed with=C2=A062.1% of t=
he vote, and Exxon went and did a report. This had some effect:=C2=A0There =
wasn=E2=80=99t a climate-change proposal in 2018, though there were proposa=
ls for a =E2=80=9Cboard diversity matrix=E2=80=9D and a =E2=80=9Creport on =
lobbying.=E2=80=9D But climate was back in 2019; here=E2=80=99s=C2=A0a 2019=
 proposal=C2=A0asking for a =E2=80=9Cnew Board Committee on Climate Change =
to evaluate Exxon Mobil=E2=80=99s strategic vision and responses to climate=
 change=E2=80=9D; it got 7.4% of the vote. And then in 2020 there was the P=
ark Foundation=E2=80=99s request for a slightly different report, which fai=
led; in 2021 there=E2=80=99s the Christian Brothers=E2=80=99 request for a =
yet slightly different report.=C2=A0This is how formal shareholder engageme=
nt generally goes: Small social-activist shareholders (individuals, religio=
us orders, activist groups)=C2=A0submit nonbinding proposals asking compani=
es to write reports or form committees, the companies urge shareholders to =
vote against the proposals, the shareholders usually vote against the propo=
sals, and then everyone does it again next year. Over the long run, the the=
ory goes, this nudges companies in the direction that the activists want: I=
t=E2=80=99s annoying and embarrassing for the companies to fight these prop=
osals every year, so to appease the activists they=E2=80=99ll occasionally =
write a report; so as not to make the report embarrassing, the company will=
 subtly change its behavior to look better. But each particular proposal ca=
n feel a bit trivial: The shareholders are only asked to make a nonbinding =
request for a report, and they usually don=E2=80=99t even do that.Exxon=E2=
=80=99s annual meeting today=C2=A0is=C2=A0different. I mean, yes, the Chris=
tian Brothers have a nonbinding proposal for a report, that=E2=80=99s the s=
ame as every year. But another activist, Engine No. 1 LLC, has a different =
proposal:Over the past decade, the Company has failed to evolve in a rapidl=
y changing world, resulting in significant underperformance to the detrimen=
t of shareholders and risking continued long-term value destruction. =E2=80=
=A6 We believe that to address this underperformance, the Company must comm=
it to evolve and chart a long-term strategic plan for sustainable value cre=
ation. In that vein, Engine No. 1, through this Proxy Statement, is providi=
ng shareholders with the opportunity to weigh in and cast their votes for a=
 slate of independent and highly qualified shareholder-nominated nominees f=
or the first time in the Company=E2=80=99s history. We believe the Nominees=
 will bring a much needed shareholder voice to the current board of directo=
rs of the Company (the =E2=80=9CBoard=E2=80=9D).This is very different from=
 the Christian Brothers. For one thing, Engine No. 1 does not own=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cshares with a market value greater than $2,000,=E2=80=9D the minimum =
threshold for a shareholder proposal; it owns 917,400 shares, worth about $=
53 million at yesterday=E2=80=99s closing price. This is not a small-stakes=
 social activist; this is an activist hedge fund.For another thing, this pr=
oposal is binding, a contested director election rather than a precatory pr=
oposal: If a majority of shares are voted for the Engine No. 1 nominees, th=
ey will be on Exxon=E2=80=99s board, and Exxon=E2=80=99s nominees won=E2=80=
=99t be. Even if it wins, Engine No. 1 will only have a minority of the boa=
rd =E2=80=94=C2=A0four out of 12 directors =E2=80=94=C2=A0so it won=E2=80=
=99t have an unchecked=C2=A0ability to push through its plans to shake up E=
xxon=E2=80=99s business, but having four directors and the confidence of th=
e majority of the shareholders is a lot more compelling than having a nonbi=
nding request for a report. And if those directors get on the board, they=
=C2=A0can=C2=A0meddle in Exxon=E2=80=99s ordinary business: They can propos=
e new ideas to the other directors, and if they win over those=C2=A0directo=
rs they can tell Exxon=E2=80=99s executives to implement those ideas and fi=
re the executives if they refuse.And that=E2=80=99s what Engine No. 1 wants=
: If it wins, it hopes to=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cimpose greater long-term capital al=
location discipline by applying more stringent approval criteria for new ca=
pital expenditures=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cimplement a strategic plan for sus=
tainable value creation by fully exploring growth areas, including more sig=
nificant investment in clean energy.=E2=80=9D That is, stop drilling for oi=
l so much, and spend more time and money on pivoting to clean energy.For a =
third thing, this proposal is expensive. Nonbinding shareholder proposals g=
et included in the company=E2=80=99s proxy statement; the activist probably=
 needs a lawyer to write the proposal and debate the company=E2=80=99s effo=
rts to exclude it, but you can basically do it as a hobby. Proxy fights ove=
r directors are waged using separate proxy statements and a lot of vote can=
vassing; the activist needs to prepare and file a detailed proxy statement,=
 keep up a steady stream of filings, letters and press releases,=C2=A0and h=
ire people to solicit votes:Since January, Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s bid for f=
our seats on Exxon=E2=80=99s board has turned into one of the most expensiv=
e proxy fights ever. Exxon has spent at least $35 million, and Engine No. 1=
 has spent $30 million, regulatory filings show, in an increasingly pitched=
 battle to persuade shareholders voting Wednesday at the company=E2=80=99s =
annual meeting.Also it might work:The activists got a boost Tuesday when Bl=
ackRock Inc., one of Exxon=E2=80=99s largest shareholders, decided to back =
three of Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s four board nominees, according to people fa=
miliar with the matter.And:The pension systems Calpers, Calstrs and the New=
 York State Common Retirement Fund as well as the European asset manager Le=
gal & General Investment Management have said they will vote for the Engine=
 No 1 slate on Wednesday. America=E2=80=99s two largest proxy advisers this=
 month endorsed some of the hedge fund=E2=80=99s board nominees.Of course I=
 am being a bit silly comparing the Engine No. 1 proxy fight to the Christi=
an Brothers=E2=80=99 nonbinding proxy proposal. The Engine No. 1 proxy figh=
t is a=C2=A0proxy fight, comparable to the many other cases where activist =
hedge funds urge companies to change their strategies and nominate director=
 candidates to push those changes along. As with most activist-hedge-fund p=
roxy fights, Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s argument to shareholders is essentially=
 a=C2=A0business=C2=A0argument: Exxon=E2=80=99s current strategy has not ma=
de enough money for shareholders, and Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s proposed new s=
trategy will make more money for shareholders. (And as with many proxy figh=
ts, part of that business case is about =E2=80=9Ccapital allocation discipl=
ine=E2=80=9D: Activist shareholders tend to think that corporate managers l=
ove to waste shareholder money, and they tend to want companies to spend th=
at money on share buybacks instead.)But it is not quite like most proxy fig=
hts. For one thing, Exxon is a huge company and Engine No. 1 has a fairly s=
mall stake =E2=80=94=C2=A0larger than the Christian Brothers, sure, but sma=
ller than a typical activist stake. (Its $53 million stake represents about=
 0.02% of the company; it is the 182nd-biggest shareholder on Bloomberg=E2=
=80=99s holders list.) Spending $53 million on stock and $30 million on a p=
roxy fight is an odd business proposition: If your plan works and the stock=
 goes up 60%, you still lose money. Also, of course, if an=C2=A0activist sh=
areholder accumulates an 8% stake in a company and launches a proxy fight, =
it has a good start on getting the 51% of the vote it needs; Engine No. 1=
=E2=80=99s 0.02% doesn=E2=80=99t help much.Instead, Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s =
business case for change is not a=C2=A0pure=C2=A0business case; it is also =
an ESG case for change, a push into green energy that appeals to investors =
interested in environmental, social and governance issues:=E2=80=9CThis cou=
ld be a landmark moment for the investment and oil industries alike,=E2=80=
=9D said Edward Mason, director of engagement at Generation Investment Mana=
gement. =E2=80=9CIf Engine No 1 candidates are elected, responsible investm=
ent will truly have shown its muscle and the import of investor net zero co=
mmitments will be clear.=E2=80=9DBlackRock, Exxon=E2=80=99s second-biggest =
shareholder, has  talked a lot about climate change, but it has developed a=
 reputation=C2=A0for voting against too many nonbinding requests for climat=
e reports. Voting for a=C2=A0binding clean-energy=C2=A0proposal at=C2=A0a g=
iant oil company will help change that reputation.=C2=A0I have said this be=
fore, but there are basically two kinds of =E2=80=9Cactivism=E2=80=9D in in=
vesting. One is what the Christian Brothers and As You Sow do: social activ=
ism, nonbinding requests that companies issue reports on environmental, soc=
ial and governance issues. The other is what, like, Carl Icahn does: hedge-=
fund activism, proxy fights to take control of companies and push them to c=
hange strategies to make more money for shareholders. As ESG becomes more m=
ainstream, and as giant investors (1) come to believe that ESG improvements=
 are good for long-term shareholder value and (2) want to vote for ESG impr=
ovements=C2=A0in any case=C2=A0to burnish their own ESG credentials, there =
is an opportunity for a synthesis: You can do hedge-fund activism to take c=
ontrol of companies and change their businesses, by focusing specifically o=
n environmental issues. That=E2=80=99s what Engine No. 1 is trying, and it =
might work.A bank hearingOccasionally banks do terrible things and their ch=
ief executive officers are summoned before Congress to be yelled at, and th=
at can be fun. But today the CEOs of the big U.S. banks are going to Congre=
ss to get yelled at for no particular reason, just because Congress likes t=
o do that every year whether or not there=E2=80=99s any news. =E2=80=9CAnnu=
al Oversight of Wall Street Firms,=E2=80=9D it is called, and you can watch=
 the video and read the CEOs=E2=80=99 written testimony here.In the absence=
 of juicy banking news it all  feels pretty=C2=A0miscellaneous. Here, for i=
nstance, is the testimony of Morgan Stanley CEO James Gorman, which contain=
s specific responses to questions from Senate Banking Committee Chairman Sh=
errod Brown, and the questions are mostly not in the vein of, like, =E2=80=
=9Cwhy did you build complex derivatives that were designed to fail=E2=80=
=9D or whatever but rather =E2=80=9Cwhat are you doing about climate change=
? And Covid? And systemic racism in America?=E2=80=9D Also one question is =
effectively =E2=80=9Care you breaking any laws we should know about?=E2=80=
=9D A sampling:Describe your state of compliance with all applicable laws a=
nd process made to address past violations of law.Provide an assessment of =
your firm=E2=80=99s efforts to accelerate the transition to a green economy=
, by reduction in investment and funding of carbon intensive industries, in=
creased investment in green technologies, and efforts to decrease carbon em=
issions.Assessment of your firm=E2=80=99s response to the non-financial eco=
nomy=E2=80=99s needs throughout the COVID-19 pandemic.Provide an assessment=
 of your firm=E2=80=99s efforts to identify and alter policies and practice=
s by your institution that contribute to systemic racism and inequality. Di=
scuss the impacts of your firm=E2=80=99s lending, investment, and trading a=
ctivities on racial and economic inequality in the broader economy generall=
y and in labor markets specifically.You could have a model of big banks tha=
t is like =E2=80=9Ca bank is a reluctant arm of the government.=E2=80=9D (A=
 quite respectable model is that  banks are public utilities, private busin=
esses with a special government franchise that comes with benefits and obli=
gations.)=C2=A0All sorts of government policies and goals =E2=80=94=C2=A0mo=
netary and fiscal policy in particular, but also efforts at Covid relief an=
d racial diversity and climate-change mitigation and foreign-policy sanctio=
ns and policies on  gun control and fights against terrorism and  sex traff=
icking=C2=A0and lots of other things =E2=80=94=C2=A0can be transmitted thro=
ugh banks. Often, if a politician wants some improvement on some=C2=A0polic=
y goal, it is easier to get results by yelling at banks for a while than by=
 passing legislation.This makes for surly hearings: The banks want to be le=
ft alone to make money; the politicians want the banks to put aside their s=
elf-interest and serve the public good. But they are safer ground for the b=
anks than the other kind of hearing. =E2=80=9CWe want someone to end system=
ic racism and stop climate change, why aren=E2=80=99t you doing that?=E2=80=
=9D is a better question, for a bank CEO, than =E2=80=9Cwhy did you lose al=
l that money on a bad trade?=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhy did your customers lo=
se all that money on a trade you put them in?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Win by losingA =
somewhat tongue-in-cheek but surprisingly useful maxim of high finance is t=
hat it is good for your career if you lose a billion dollars. I mean, if yo=
u lose a billion dollars for your employer you will probably be fired, thou=
gh that depends on who your employer is and how much money you started with=
 and what you did to lose it. But lots of=C2=A0other employers=C2=A0will be=
 excited to hire you, once they learn that you lost a billion dollars for s=
omeone else. That is a good sign in a lot of ways:=09It shows that someone =
trusted you to take risks with a lot of money. That=E2=80=99s good! An empl=
oyer is going to be nervous about letting anyone take billion-dollar risks =
with its money; if someone=C2=A0else=C2=A0already let you take billion-doll=
ar risks with their money then that is evidence that you are one of the peo=
ple=C2=A0sensible employers trust to take billion-dollar risks. Of course i=
t went poorly for your last employer but that=E2=80=99s not the point.=09It=
 shows that you were willing to take risks. That=E2=80=99s good! Financial =
firms want people who will do stuff, who will make bold bets, who will take=
 a chance at failing. It=E2=80=99s easy enough to sit around looking busy w=
hile basically tracking an index; losing a billion dollars means that you w=
ere bold and active.=09Sure sure the risks didn=E2=80=99t work out but you =
probably have a good story about why it seemed like a good idea ex ante.=09=
You have probably learned from your mistakes and won=E2=80=99t do it again.=
 (You probably also, now, have a good story about why it=C2=A0wasn=E2=80=99=
t=C2=A0a good idea ex ante.[1])=09A weird optional bonus is that if you los=
t a billion dollars for a big employer, you might have some insights into h=
ow to=C2=A0take=C2=A0a billion dollars from that employer, which is potenti=
ally useful for that employer=E2=80=99s competitors. Not all of finance is,=
 like, Hedge Fund A figuring out how to exploit Bank B=E2=80=99s=C2=A0weakn=
esses, but=C2=A0some=C2=A0of it is, and if you=C2=A0were=C2=A0one of Bank B=
=E2=80=99s weaknesses you might be of particular use to Hedge Fund A.People=
 talk about the asymmetric incentives for risk-takers at banks =E2=80=94 if=
 you take a lot of risk and it works out, you get a huge bonus; if you take=
 a lot of risk and it blows up, the worst they can do is fire you =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but if this maxim is true (and, again, it=E2=80=99s partly a joke) th=
en it's even stronger than that, because if you take a lot of risk and it b=
lows up that=E2=80=99s good for you too. You=E2=80=99re not just long a cal=
l on your performance, you=E2=80=99re somehow also long a put. Either way y=
ou profit from volatility, so=C2=A0your incentive is to take a lot of risk.=
[2]I don=E2=80=99t literally mean =E2=80=9Ca billion dollars,=E2=80=9D by t=
he way; that=E2=80=99s a nice round number and certainly attracts attention=
 from future employers, but you can achieve similar career goals with some =
other large salient loss. Anyway here=E2=80=99s a fun story about  the new =
chief financial officer of JPMorgan Chase & Co.:Long before Jeremy Barnum w=
as promoted to chief financial officer, he was fired over a trading mishap =
-- by JPMorgan. He later parted ways with hedge fund BlueMountain Capital M=
anagement over another market blunder. ...[In 2004], JPMorgan=E2=80=99s res=
ults in fixed income faltered. When Barnum=E2=80=99s [credit derivatives[ t=
eam lost a bundle, his name was added to a list of dismissals as the bank=
=E2=80=99s bosses set out to restructure the unit. He sent coworkers a tong=
ue-in-cheek farewell email recommending that they closely study the career =
of Joseph Stalin=E2=80=99s henchman Lavrentiy Beria and get really good at =
PowerPoint.Barnum was soon snapped up by BlueMountain, which named him head=
 of its London office in 2005. The next year, the fund took a bath on wrong=
-way credit bets linked to Liberty Global Inc.=E2=80=99s Cablecom Holdings,=
 prompting another ouster for Barnum. In a statement at the time, a senior =
BlueMountain executive said Barnum=E2=80=99s exit was =E2=80=9Cmutually agr=
eed.=E2=80=9DThen came the uncanny turnaround. JPMorgan gave Barnum a secon=
d chance and a new mission: Instead of making wagers himself, Barnum would =
use his trading experience and the lessons he learned to help oversee busin=
esses, spot risks and head off trouble. He rejoined JPMorgan in 2007, right=
 as two of Bear Stearns Cos.=E2=80=99 hedge funds were blowing up.By 2010, =
Barnum was indispensable to his bosses and on the rise, having helped the f=
irm dodge bullets from the financial crisis.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThis guy knows h=
ow we lose money,=E2=80=9D was I guess the theory; =E2=80=9Cmaybe he can al=
so stop us from losing money.=E2=80=9D It worked!By the way, my favorite th=
ing in financial-industry profiles is=C2=A0the unwritten rule that everyone=
 except Chase Coleman has to be described as not fitting in with all those =
other, stereotypical bankers and hedge funders. The classic of the genre is=
, like, Warren Buffett lives in a normal house, but lots of bankers and hed=
ge-fund managers in fact live in fancy houses so you have to stretch a litt=
le.=C2=A0There is the  hedge-fund consultant whose =E2=80=9Cmost obvious in=
dulgence is a Maserati Ghibli,=E2=80=9D or the hedge-fund manager whose =E2=
=80=9Cunique position, with one foot inside the lucrative hedge-fund indust=
ry and one foot out of it, is perhaps most plain on weekends during the sum=
mer,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0when =E2=80=94=C2=A0I swear =E2=80=94=C2=A0he only=C2=A0=
sometimes=C2=A0takes a private plane to his house on Nantucket. (Other time=
s, he flies commercial.) Barnum=C2=A0is unique because, although like a lot=
 of people in finance he went to Groton and Harvard and then straight to JP=
Morgan, he has a=C2=A0posher accent than everyone else:=E2=80=9CYou get to =
know him a little bit and he=E2=80=99s just different than all the other Gr=
oton and Harvard people,=E2=80=9D said Gus Christensen, a former banker who=
 left Wall Street for politics. They=E2=80=99ve been friends since joining =
the bank together in 1994, when Barnum, armed with a chemistry degree, show=
ed up in a second-hand Brooks Brothers suit.Christensen and others noted th=
at Barnum=E2=80=99s time overseas had left him talking differently from his=
 peers. =E2=80=9CHe speaks like a movie actor in the 1930s -- he has a litt=
le bit of a lockjaw. It=E2=80=99s not a way of speaking in English that I h=
ad heard from anyone else in my generation,=E2=80=9D Christensen said. =E2=
=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s much more subtle now than it was then.=E2=80=9DWell this=
 is ominousNFT dot gamestop dot com, huh. =E2=80=9CGameStop NFT,=E2=80=9D i=
t says. =E2=80=9CChange the Game.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWe are building a team.=
 We welcome exceptional engineers (solidity, react, python), designers, gam=
ers, marketers, and community leaders.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Look, fine, whatever; =
three things are true:=09Non-fungible tokens representing unique entitlemen=
ts to digital-only assets are in some sense a natively video-game concept. =
If you play an   immersive multiplayer video game, and you spend hours play=
ing and are deeply invested in your character and care deeply about her suc=
cess and happiness, you might think nothing of spending millions of in-game=
 currency units, or tens of U.S. dollars, buying things that she needs or w=
ants, or buying unique in-game items that give her an aura of distinction a=
nd power. Or you could play a video game in which you  collect different ca=
ts, sure, right, =E2=80=9Cgo around collecting digital objects=E2=80=9D is =
a classic sort of gameplay. The items that you are buying and collecting ar=
e pure digital artifacts that live on some online=C2=A0platform; saying tha=
t you have a unique entitlement to them, and that some bit of code can=C2=
=A0represent both=C2=A0the digital object and=C2=A0your entitlement to it, =
seems normal and intuitive.=C2=A0There are of course other uses for NFTs, a=
nd I think that they tend to make more sense the closer they come to=C2=A0c=
lassic sorts of gaming and leisure collecting activities. NFTs as a complic=
ated form=C2=A0of=C2=A0in-game video-game items, sure. NFTs as a complicate=
d form of   baseball cards and sports memorabilia, sure. NFTs as a complica=
ted form of   conceptual art, yes, look, that=E2=80=99s okay but kind of pu=
shing it. NFTs that  create entitlements to real objects in the real world =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0I dunno, maybe, but to my mind you could just trade the real=
 objects, or the real entitlements, and dispense with the mystification of =
the NFT. I guess the point here is that if your business model is =E2=80=9C=
we will somehow execute a vague pivot into being   the future of online vid=
eo gaming,=E2=80=9D NFTs seem like a reasonable sort of pivot.=09There is a=
 huge vogue for NFTs right now, or at least there was a month or two ago, a=
nd you can sell all sorts of NFTs for wild prices.=09There is a huge vogue =
for GameStop right now, or at least there was a few months=C2=A0ago, and yo=
u can sell all sorts of stories about GameStop for wild prices.I don=E2=80=
=99t know that those three facts add up to anything, but after writing them=
 down next to each other like that I guess, yeah, if I were GameStop I=E2=
=80=99d hire some NFT developers too.GameStop Corp. common stock closed at =
$209.43 yesterday, up 16.3% on the day. It was  up more this morning:GameSt=
op shares rallied as much as 10.3% to $231.04 at 9:32 a.m. in New York whil=
e AMC rose 9.7% to $18, adding to recent gains. The jumps came as investors=
 increasingly touted the stocks on social media platforms, using hashtags l=
ike #AMC500k on Twitter and pumping their bets in trader chatrooms on Stock=
twits and Reddit=E2=80=99s WallStreetBets.=E2=80=9CIt looks like the Reddit=
 Raiders are at it again,=E2=80=9D says Michael Pachter, analyst at Wedbush=
 Securities. The pair of companies were among the market=E2=80=99s most act=
ively traded stocks early Wednesday after volumes continued to soar.I hope =
that GameStop=E2=80=99s NFT developers are working on an NFT of, like, =E2=
=80=9Cthat time that GameStop became the hottest stock in the world and the=
n stayed that way for months.=E2=80=9D That does feel like the sort of even=
t you=E2=80=99d want to commemorate on the blockchain.Things happenAmazon A=
grees to  Buy MGM Film Studio for $8.45 Billion. =E2=80=98It=E2=80=99s wild=
 out there=E2=80=99: crypto firms lure top bankers in price boom. Meet the =
Hedge Fund Boss Who Just Bought Tribune=E2=80=99s Newspapers. UniCredit  Bo=
nd Coupon Chaos Dents Orcel=E2=80=99s High-Energy Start. Central Banks Face=
 New Balancing Act With Their  Huge Asset Piles. Video Spinoff  Vimeo Slump=
s in Nasdaq Trading Debut. Traders Shouldn=E2=80=99t Get Prison Time in Spo=
ofing Case, Probation Office Says. Ex-High School Classmates Are Among the =
World=E2=80=99s Largest  Crypto Holders. Iran  Bans Crypto Mining to Keep t=
he Lights on Over Summer. Workers Return to  Weirder Offices With Moveable =
Walls and Touchless Elevators. =E2=80=9CThe scriptures of the sage Levine, =
who spoke of worrying omens of bond market liquidity, fall under this categ=
ory.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s fascinating is that, in my own way, I=
=E2=80=99ve been renting the runway for years.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CAnd whethe=
r you're a person or an inanimate object, if it moves, bulls want to make i=
t stop moving. Which is great for us.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0When to Watch the Super=
 Flower Blood Moon Lunar Eclipse 2021 Tonight.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Mon=
ey=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0su=
bscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great B=
loomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] Or not, maybe you are like =E2=80=9Ct=
hat was the correct call, the odds were in my favor, the dice rolled the wr=
ong way but I=E2=80=99d take that bet 100 more times any day.=E2=80=9D I fe=
el like that attitude =E2=80=94=C2=A0which in the abstract might be correct=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0would make it harder for you to get a new job, but what do =
I know, somebody will appreciate it.[2]=C2=A0Arguably this is the point: Ar=
guably the optimal level of risk-taking=C2=A0for a bank trader or hedge-fun=
d portfolio manager is higher than the natural risk tolerance of the sorts =
of highly educated prestige-seeking people who are eligible for those roles=
, so it is good for their employers to say =E2=80=9Cgo ahead, take risk, if=
 it works out you=E2=80=99ll do great and if it doesn=E2=80=99t you=E2=80=
=99ll also do great.=E2=80=9D Obviously lots of people outside the financia=
l industry disagree.
