color: #ccc;">got 7.4%</a> of the vote. And then in 2020 there was the Park=
 Foundation=E2=80=99s request for a slightly different report, which failed=
; in 2021 there=E2=80=99s the Christian Brothers=E2=80=99 request for a yet=
 slightly different report.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is h=
ow formal shareholder engagement generally goes: Small social-activist shar=
eholders (individuals, religious orders, activist groups)=C2=A0submit nonbi=
nding proposals asking companies to write reports or form committees, the c=
ompanies urge shareholders to vote against the proposals, the shareholders =
usually vote against the proposals, and then everyone does it again next ye=
ar. Over the long run, the theory goes, this nudges companies in the direct=
ion that the activists want: It=E2=80=99s annoying and embarrassing for the=
 companies to fight these proposals every year, so to appease the activists=
 they=E2=80=99ll occasionally write a report; so as not to make the report =
embarrassing, the company will subtly change its behavior to look better. B=
ut each particular proposal can feel a bit trivial: The shareholders are on=
ly asked to make a nonbinding request for a report, and they usually don=E2=
=80=99t even do that.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Exxon=E2=80=99s annua=
l meeting today=C2=A0is=C2=A0different. I mean, yes, the Christian Brothers=
 have a nonbinding proposal for a report, that=E2=80=99s the same as every =
year. But another activist, Engine No. 1 LLC, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/23970292.271103/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmN=
oaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzM0MDg4LzAwMDA5MDI2NjQyMTAwMTkzMS9wMjEtMDk1N2RlZmMxNG=
EuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2b2eeb24" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">has a different proposal</a>:</p><blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the past decade, the Company has faile=
d to evolve in a rapidly changing world, resulting in significant underperf=
ormance to the detriment of shareholders and risking continued long-term va=
lue destruction. =E2=80=A6 We believe that to address this underperformance=
, the Company must commit to evolve and chart a long-term strategic plan fo=
r sustainable value creation. In that vein, Engine No. 1, through this Prox=
y Statement, is providing shareholders with the opportunity to weigh in and=
 cast their votes for a slate of independent and highly qualified sharehold=
er-nominated nominees for the first time in the Company=E2=80=99s history. =
We believe the Nominees will bring a much needed shareholder voice to the c=
urrent board of directors of the Company (the =E2=80=9CBoard=E2=80=9D).</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is very different from the C=
hristian Brothers. For one thing, Engine No. 1 does not own=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cs=
hares with a market value greater than $2,000,=E2=80=9D the minimum thresho=
ld for a shareholder proposal; it owns <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/23970292.271103/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy=
9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzM0MDg4LzAwMDA5MDI2NjQyMTAwMTkzMS9wMjEtMDk1N2RlZmMxNGEuaHRt/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC2b2eeb24" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" title=3D"page 21" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">917,400 shares</a>, worth about =
$53 million at yesterday=E2=80=99s closing price. This is not a small-stake=
s social activist; this is an activist hedge fund.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">For another thing, this proposal is <em>binding</em>, a contested d=
irector election rather than a precatory proposal: If a majority of shares =
are voted for the Engine No. 1 nominees, they will be on Exxon=E2=80=99s bo=
ard, and Exxon=E2=80=99s nominees won=E2=80=99t be. Even if it wins, Engine=
 No. 1 will only have a minority of the board =E2=80=94=C2=A0four out of 12=
 directors =E2=80=94=C2=A0so it won=E2=80=99t have an unchecked=C2=A0abilit=
y to push through its plans to shake up Exxon=E2=80=99s business, but havin=
g four directors and the confidence of the majority of the shareholders is =
a lot more compelling than having a nonbinding request for a report. And if=
 those directors get on the board, they=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>meddle in Ex=
xon=E2=80=99s ordinary business: They can propose new ideas to the other di=
rectors, and if they win over those=C2=A0directors they can tell Exxon=E2=
=80=99s executives to implement those ideas and fire the executives if they=
